{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627315"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17111"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17111"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.29,0.19,0.1,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77017"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9801"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17111"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62523"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5045"},{"type":"tags","id":"7603"},{"type":"tags","id":"8412"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23112"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39399"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77017"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETocolytic medications are used to suppress uterine contractions in the management of preterm labour. Salbutamol, a beta-2 adrenergic receptor agonist, is one such medication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of salbutamol in uterine smooth muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases intracellular calcium concentration","Blocks voltage-gated sodium channels","Blocks oxytocin receptors","Inhibits prostaglandin synthesis","Increases intracellular cyclic adenosine monophosphate"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased intracellular cyclic adenosine monophosphate\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism by which beta-2 adrenergic receptor agonists like salbutamol produce uterine smooth muscle relaxation. This occurs through activation of adenylate cyclase following beta-2 receptor stimulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases intracellular calcium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E would promote rather than inhibit uterine contractions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks voltage-gated sodium channels\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism involved in tocolysis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks oxytocin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of atosiban, not salbutamol\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits prostaglandin synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is how non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs work\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased cyclic adenosine monophosphate leads to decreased intracellular calcium and myometrial relaxation. This helps delay delivery to allow time for antenatal corticosteroid administration to promote foetal lung maturity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Beta-2 adrenergic receptor agonists like salbutamol relax uterine smooth muscle by increasing intracellular cyclic adenosine monophosphate.","Calcium channel blockers prevent uterine contractions by reducing calcium influx into myometrial cells.","Tocolytic medications are used to delay delivery in preterm labour to allow time for corticosteroid administration."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62523"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17111"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62523","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62523"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:27:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:30:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9801"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77017"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ